DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PCCmacros.pl", "parserLinearRelation.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context("LinearRelation")->variables->are(x => 'Real'); $equation = LinearRelation("x - 0.37x > 25957");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML You read on the internet that from the year 2010 to the year 2023, community colleges experienced over [`37\%`] enrollment decline. In spring 2023 at Portland Community College, there were [`25{,}957`] students. Write an inequality where the solution set represents how many students may have been at PCC in spring 2010.
[@KeyboardInstructions('Use [|x|]* for the variable.')@]**
[_]{$equation}{25}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION We decide to let [`x`] represent the number of students enrolled at PCC in spring 2010. This is an "initial value" in the sense of (1.1.2). But we do not want to write an equation, because we were told that community colleges experienced _over_ a [`37\%`] enrollment decline, not exactly a [`37\%`] decline. So we write the following:
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} \text{initialValue} \pm \text{rate}\cdot\text{initialValue} \amp\mathrel{?} \text{finalValue}\\ x - 0.37x \amp\mathrel{?} 25957 \end{aligned} ```]
But what inequality symbol makes sense here? If the decline was _more_ than [`37\%\text{,}`] then [`x`] started out larger than what it would have to be for [`x - 0.37x`] to equal [`25957\text{.}`] So we need a greater than sign:
[```\newcommand{\gt}{>} x - 0.37x \gt 25957 ```]
Once again, we will not try to solve this at this time.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
